<TEXT>
a sandinista negotiator on wednesday 
accused the contras of maneuvering to avoid a permanent ceasefire 
and keep receiving us aid 
we have serious doubts they want to enter into a definitive 
ceasefire deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco told a 
news conference 
they simply want to move into zones which means gains for them 
without a threat with security and to gain the release of 50 
percent of the prisoners american aid and participation in 
politics 
there was no immediate response from the rebels the government 
and contras have been arguing by letter about ceasefire talks 
jeopardizing a meeting set for friday that would be their first in 
managua since the war began in 1981 
the contras suggested in a letter wednesday that a meeting on 
implementation of the ceasefire be held thursday at sapoa a 
southern border post where a provisional truce was signed march 23 
and they threatened to boycott the friday meeting in the capital 
earlier this week they wanted the technical meeting held wednesday 
in a letter sent tuesday night to contra leaders in miami 
officials of the leftist sandinista government said talks on 
technical aspects of the truce should be held in managua on 
wednesday and that fridays highlevel meeting should go ahead as 
planned 
nicaraguan officials and the ussupported rebels also disagree 
on where contra delegates should stay while in managua and what 
they should be allowed to do 
the technical talks in sapoa broke down last friday after six 
rounds in which the two sides agreed only on seven zones to which 
contra fighters would be confined during the 60day truce 
still to be worked out are security for the rebels in those 
zones methods of resupplying them and other details of their 
existence during the two months allowed for negotiating a permanent 
ceasefire 
rebel fighters had been scheduled to be in the zones by this 
friday but they have not even begun gathering officials say they 
will free a second group of political prisoners when the contras 
are in the zones 
nicaragua is estimated to have more than 3000 political 
prisoners the sandinistas released 100 soon after the provisional 
truce was signed 
the truce began april 1 since then the sides have exchanged 
heated arguments but reached no agreement on ways to end the war 
on wednesday the contras said in a letter to defense minister 
humberto ortega that the friday meeting was subject to the 
results of the technical meetings at sapoa they contend there is 
nothing for leaders to discuss until the mechanical operation 
of the zones is resolved 
rebel leaders adolfo calero and pedro joaquin chamorro signed 
the letter which said the contra delegation had reservations at 
the intercontinental hotel in downtown managua the sandinistas 
want the contras at a governmentowned hotel near the airport 
because it has all the necessary requirements 
calero and chamorro said contra delegates also demand the 
freeedom to meet with civic and political organizations during 
their three days in managua 
sandinista officials say the truce agreement makes clear that 
contras can enter political life only after their combatants are in 
the ceasefire zones 
