<TEXT>
a key legal decision puts the national 
archives one step closer to letting the public see presidential 
papers that richard m nixon wants kept secret 
the decision tuesday by the us court of appeals in washington 
knocks down a reagan administration attempt to force the archives 
to honor automatically all nixon claims of executive privilege 
it restores a regulation that says an archives review board will 
study disputes over executive privilege claimed by nixon and that 
the former president must go to court if he wants to overturn a 
board decision 
although 3 million pages of nixon documents have been opened to 
researchers nixon and his lawyers have been able to withhold 
150000 documents by claiming they involved executive privilege 
private political associations personal property or personal 
privilege 
a representative of nixons lawyers spent three years in the 
archives warehouse in alexandria va identifying documents to be 
excluded from public view the requests for exemption from 
disclosure totaled 3100 pages and the protected papers represent 
about 10 percent of the 15 million pages in the socalled nixon 
special files which contained the most sensitive documents 
the justice department did not decide immediately whether to 
carry the case to the supreme court weve got 90 days to make 
any decision said michael carvin a justice department lawyer 
who helped prepare the appeal of a lower court decision 
gary brooks legal counsel for the archives said processing of 
nixon documents had continued while the case was in the court the 
archives must now set up a presidential materials review board 
consisting of the archivist two assistant archivists the legal 
counsel and a historian of a federal agency 
the problem is nixons objections tend to overlap brooks 
said on one document there may be three different types of 
objections 
congress seized the papers 42 million pages and 880 tape 
recordings in 1974 after nixon resigned from the presidency the 
act directed that they be made public to disclose the full 
truth about watergate 
there followed years of legal wrangling over access regulations 
five sets of rules were invalidated for various reasons when the 
sixth set the regulations now in effect was presented to the 
reagan administration the justice departments office of legal 
counsel added what the court called its gloss to the rules 
the olc demanded that if either an incumbent president or nixon 
were to claim executive privilege for any document the archivist 
would be obliged to honor that claim the rule put the burden of 
challenging that decision on the person requesting the material 
tuesdays action reverses that procedure 
ronald reagan not richard nixon is the constitutional 
superior of the archivist the court said in its ruling ronald 
reagan has the constitutional power to direct the archivist not 
richard nixon 
the ruling said nixon must ask to withhold documents on a 
disclosurebydisclosure basis it also rejected nixons claim 
that someone requesting the materials must show a particular need 
for them 
the opinion was written by circuit judge laurence silberman a 
reagan administration appointee who has supported expanding 
executive branch authority since joining the court most recently 
he wrote an opinion striking down the law providing that 
independent counsels rather than the justice department would 
investigate executive branch officials accused of wrongdoing 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

