have staged protests on tiananmen square in central beijing 
daringly placing their careers on the line 
their message to the government give more money to education 
one group came with shoeshine kits to parody government 
suggestions that students and faculty work to supplement the 
schools meager budgets 
another group came with signs in english and chinese saying 
we want more money for education 
at beijing university chinas most prestigious posters have 
appeared saying that current financial strictures have made it 
useless to study just as political oppression did during the 
cultural revolution of 196575 
the academics timed their protests to coincide with the national 
peoples congress chinas legislature which today concluded an 
annual 20day session 
although the shoeshiners were quickly escorted by police off the 
square officers allowed the sitin by 19 students and teachers 
more important delegates to the congress acknowledged the 
protesters grievances are real 
xu jialu a delegate and vice president of beijing normal 
university questioned the congress about the policy whereby 
associate professors earn 33 a month is he or she worth so 
little 
shanghai delegates spoke of the devaluation of 
intellectuals and former congress vice chairman zhou gucheng said 
some academics cant even afford to buy dictionaries all this 
should not continue if the country wishes to develop he said 
the response to the protests has been markedly different from 
the conservative backlash that followed much larger prodemocracy 
student demonstrations in december 1986 and january 1987 
at that time students were arrested and hu yaobang the 
communist party head was purged from his post 
since then political activism has died out on campuses with 
students cowed by increased surveillance and threats of poor job 
assignments upon graduation 
the recent protests have avoided trouble because they have 
stayed away from politically sensitive areas they also came at a 
time when some powerful officials are pushing for more money for 
education 
the current government of senior leader deng xiaoping and 
communist party head zhao ziyang has recognized that intellectuals 
are crucial to the nations economic development and has tried to 
raise their social status 
last year millions of teachers and scientists were given 10 
percent pay raises their first in years 
but xu pei a young teacher demonstrating on tiananmen square on 
sunday told canadian television that living conditions for 
teachers remain terribly poor you cant imagine for instance a 
whole family with three or four or five members living in a small 
room about 10 square meters 110 square feet 
xu who said he earns 24 a month considerably less than a 
manual laborer at a profitable factory said he didnt want special 
treatment for teachers 
we only want teachers to get equal pay with other walks of 
society we think we are low we are mistreated 
educators say inadequate state funding for chinas 640000 
undergraduate and 45000 graduate students is seriously undermining 
academic achievment 
the state allocates around 485 a year for an undergraduate and 
1080 to 1620 for research students 
funding for education is to be boosted by 12 percent this year 
but much of that is for the daunting task of improving 
elementarylevel education in rural areas where 200 million people 
20 percent of all chinese remain illiterate 
party chief zhao has told institutes of higher education that 
they will have to fend for themselves saying it is necessary and 
possible for them to earn money by setting up factories and 
providing other services to society 
the state education commission also has proposed the financial 
crunch be eased by having students who now receive basically free 
educations pay their own tuition and be responsible for finding 
their own jobs when they graduate 
by 1993 according to one plan 70 percent of undergraduates 
will be paying tuition or will be sponsored by companies that will 
hire them after their studies are completed 
the reform also designed to motivate students to study more is 
generally accepted as necessary but qualms remain 
students said demonstrator xu now cant see any future 
for them because upon graduation they cant hope to make as much 
money as a worker 
