<TEXT>
congress bears a responsibility to see that 
children dependent on high technology machines to stay alive 
receive the care they need at home when possible says a federal 
task force 
the report issued tuesday makes no estimate of what such an 
approach would cost and acknowledges that bringing about the 
resolution it recommends will depend on generating public pressure 
for changes 
advocates must give special emphasis to raising public 
awareness of these children and the special issues affecting their 
care said the report by the task force on technology dependent 
children 
rep thomas j tauke riowa who was among those pushing for 
creation of the task force 18 months ago acknowledged to the head 
of the panel at a news conference that you have thrown a good 
portion of the challenge back to congress 
i will try to make sure these recommendations do not die on 
the vine tauke said at a news conference this report is going 
to put additional pressure on congress to respond to the need 
at the same time tauke said there is little likelihood of 
action this year with congress aiming for adjournment in advance of 
the november elections 
the task force said congress should 
develop and implement legislative strategies for ensuring 
access to programs that meet the individual needs of 
technologydependent children 
develop legislative strategies requiring all public and 
private payers that finance health care for technologydependent 
children to develop appropriate measures for ending 
institutional bias within these programs 
creation of the task force stemmed partly from the katie beckett 
case in 1981 medicaid rules in effect at the time kept her from 
being cared for at home at a cost of about 2000 a month but it 
was costing about 12000 a month to keep her in a hospital 
when the case came to president reagans attention he told 
aides in a widely publicized episode to find a way to cut through 
the red tape 
tauke said katie now 10 lives at home attends school and 
sings in her church choir 
for every katie thriving at home we still have many children 
in hospital wards tauke added 
administrative changes made since 1981 allow states more leeway 
in deciding how to spend medicaid dollars on such children who are 
dependent on machines to help them breathe as katie was or 
maintain other life sustaining functions 
estimates of the number of children who require such care range 
from 2300 to 17000 depending on the level of technology needed 
but the report says fewer than 400 are being cared for at home 
under the medicaid waivers now allowed 
the task force defined a technologydependent child as one 
requiring use of a specific medical device to compensate for loss 
of a lifesustaining function and one who requires daily ongoing 
care or monitoring by trained personnel 
were not talking about hearing aides or crutches said dr 
robert g kettrick the task force chairman who emphasized that 
drawing such a specific definition for the first time was in itself 
a significant step 
also for the first time it defines appropriate care as 
whatever is required to maintain life support and provide an 
environment conducive to growth and development it spells out 
that such a treatment plan is to be documented and managed 
through the use of an individualized plan developed and monitored 
by a team which includes parents or guardians 
</TEXT>
