<TEXT>
senators debating the 11 trillion federal 
budget for fiscal 1989 with few disputes over its details are 
questioning whether the spending plan accurately portrays the 
governments deficit 
the lawmakers hoped to complete work today on a budget blueprint 
in which the key questions about taxes and domestic defense and 
foreign assistance spending have already been settled 
during tuesdays second day of debate over the proposal some 
senators examined its projected 136 billion deficit and pronounced 
the budget misleading 
the 136 billion figure is crucial because that is the 1989 
deficit target set by the grammrudman balanced budget law should 
the deficit exceed that figure by 10 billion spending would 
automatically be cut across the board to the target level 
the problem said legislators was that the figure includes 
surpluses being stashed away by several government programs such 
as social security in which money is set aside for specific 
purposes 
the legislators argued that since those funds can be spent for 
nothing else it is deceptive to use them to reduce the 
governments red ink 
there is nothing less to call this but fraud said sen 
ernest hollings dsc 
in an 858 vote tuesday the senate gave preliminary approval to 
a nonbinding amendment urging lawmakers to discount the special 
highway and aviation funds when determining the size of the 
deficit those programs are expected to garner a 2 billion surplus 
in fiscal 1989 which begins oct 1 
sen lawton chiles dfla chairman of the budget committee 
has introduced another provision aimed at persuading senators not 
to count social security when computing the deficit 
social security which is accumulating money for the retirement 
of the baby boom generation in the early 21st century is expected 
to run a 46 billion surplus next year 
the budget itself contains little that is controversial largely 
because last falls summit agreement between president reagan and 
congressional leaders answered most of the questions that have 
sparked months of bitter debate in the past 
as a result congress work on the budget resolution is expected 
to be completed earlier than it has in years 
the senates spending plan calls for 294 billion in military 
spending 161 billion for foreign assistance and 1692 billion 
for domestic programs set by automatic formulas 
it also includes 14 billion in new taxes called for by the 
summit agreement and already enacted 
the major differences between the senate proposal and the 
version reagan sent congress in february are over domestic 
priorities the lawmakers would provide money for several 
development and transportation programs that the president sought 
to eliminate or slash severely 
the senators would increase space and science spending by about 
onefourth and also dramatically increase money for aids research 
education and drug enforcement 
their budget would also increase military salaries by 43 
percent and pay for civilian workers by 2 percent spend 500 
million for more farm commodities for the poor permit expansion of 
the medicaid health program and enactment of medicare catastrophic 
illness insurance and cut rural housing assistance elderly 
housing and community and regional development 
the house approved a similar version of the budget last month 
congress two chambers must ultimately approve identical budget 
resolutions but the presidents signature is not required 
