<TEXT>
the closing of this years national peoples 
congress with its stress on reforms marks the end of the career 
of peng zhen a stodgy conservative who made the legislature into a 
force to be reckoned with 
pengs fiveyear term as chairman officially ended friday when 
he was replaced by reformminded former vice premier wan li 
the 86yearold peng was a harsh critic of senior leader deng 
xiaopings reforms of the past decade and developed his own power 
base in the legislature to slow down the pace of change 
he was a strong advocate of state control over economic 
political and social life in china and saw marketstyle economic 
reform and opening to the outside world as bringing in 
pernicious capitalist and western trends 
peng was believed to have been behind the january 1987 ouster of 
party chief hu yaobang who was blamed for prodemocracy student 
demonstrations staged in a dozen cities around the country that 
winter 
he was a leading figure in the campaign against bourgeois 
liberalization or western ideas that followed the protests 
several leading intellectuals were purged from the party as a 
result 
pengs leadership role in the congress began in 1979 not long 
after he returned to beijing from the mountains of shaanxi 
province where he had spent the cultural revolution years 
he was made head of the congress legislative committee and 
drafted a criminal code that was adopted the same year 
peng presented a new state constitution to the congress in 1982 
that substantially increased the powers of the legislature 
the constitution gave the congress until then a powerless and 
largely ceremonial body the power to enact laws and supervise the 
state council 
the following year peng became chairman of the legislature and 
under his leadership it began to shed its image as a rubber stamp 
for all party dictates 
peng shrugged off suggestions that he was an antideng xiaoping 
conservative and like all chinese leaders claimed loyalty to 
the idea of reform but he also openly criticized the decline of 
orthodox marxist principles and warned of the dangers of 
liberalization 
pengs official biography says he was born in 1902 to a peasant 
family in shanxi province and joined the communist party in 1923 
he rose through the party ranks acquiring a reputation for his 
organizational and administrative skills 
unlike most of his contemporaries peng did not participate in 
the long march and therefore did not establish early ties with mao 
tsetung but he was closely associated with former president liu 
shaoqi 
he became mayor of beijing in 1951 and directed mass executions 
of counterrevolutionaries in the capital that same year 
he continued to live up to his reputation for heavyhanded 
methods as one of the main forces behind a major anticrime 
campaign launched in 1983 that in four years has resulted in the 
executions of more than 10000 criminals 
peng was one of the first victims of the 196676 cultural 
revolution accused of attempting to stage a coup against mao 
he was stripped of all his posts banished for 12 years to the 
chining mountains of shaanxi province and not rehabilitated until 
1979 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

