april 11 
the baltimore sun on trade tradeoffs 
the trade bill sluicing through congress can be fairly compared 
to raw sewage passing through a water treatment plant 
at midstage in the process it is a good deal cleaner than when 
it went in but unless it is subjected to a lot more filtration it 
will not be fit for the law books 
what president reagan must guard against is the natural 
inclination of republican lawmakers to do something about 
massive trade deficits lest they be clobbered by democrats 
preaching economic nationalism 
as it stands now reagan should veto the trade bill it dilutes 
presidential authority by passing critical decisions affecting 
relations with other nations to a cabinetlevel trade 
representative who could be badgered by congress 
and its disclosure provisions could scare off foreign investors 
whose funds are needed to finance huge reaganera federal debts and 
deficits 
