a senior citizens lobby said wednesday it has 
sued the government to force it to credit 585 billion in wages to 
individuals social security accounts 
the national committee to preserve social security and medicare 
said it was unsatisfied with the governments efforts to resolve 
the discrepancies which has been costing some retirees an average 
of 17 a month 
john trollinger a spokesman for the social security 
administration said he had not seen the lawsuit and would have no 
comment but he said the administration is improving and making 
changes in the way we gather this wage information so that the 
discrepancies will be kept to an absolute minimum were 
working very diligently with the irs to resolve disrepancies from 
the past 
former congressman james roosevelt the chairman of the lobbying 
group said in a statement although the government has known 
about this problem for years its response has been wholly 
inadequate 
the problem arose after the government switched to a dual system 
for reporting employee earnings in 1978 since then employers have 
sent one set of employee earnings reports to the irs and another to 
the social security administration 
according to the general accounting office approximately 585 
billion in wages has not been properly credited to social security 
accounts from 1978 through 1984 nearly 97 million people 
including active workers and those now retired had some earnings 
that were erroneously omitted from their records 
the gao said that in a sample of cases it reviewed the typical 
retiree whose wage record was not up to date had lost an average of 
1681 a month for 31 months 
roosevelt said the discrepant reports were continuing to pile up 
at the rate of 500000 or more a year and employers are only 
required by law to retain employee wage records for four years 
the social security administration urges all workers to check 
their wage records every three years to make sure their wages were 
reported correctly they can fill out a form and receive a printout 
of past years wages credited for social security and compare that 
with their own wage records 
the group said it filed the lawsuit tuesday in us district 
court in washington 
