<TEXT>
scientists have found small residues of a 
potentially cancercausing animal drug in milk being sold in 10 
us cities a food and drug administration official said wednesday 
the drug sulfamethazine is approved for use in pork and beef 
cattle feed but is not supposed to be used in dairy cattle feed 
the levels we were finding in milk should not cause a public 
health problem but we are concerned because this is an illegal use 
and that drug must not be used in dairy cattle gerald guest 
head of the agencys center for veterinary medicine said in a 
statement 
we have been meeting with the appropriate industry groups and 
they already have programs under way to communicate this concern to 
their respective industries guest said the message is that 
sulfamethazine should not be used on dairy cattle 
fda spokesman chris lecos said the contaminated milk samples 
were taken in early march as part of an fda program to develop a 
simple and effective test that dairies can use to make sure they 
are not buying contaminated milk 
he said it was a small sampling exercise to evaluate an onsite 
milk testing technique that fda scientists believe is nearly ready 
for widespread use in detecting prohibited use of the drug in dairy 
cattle 
fda officials conducting the survey bought pasteurized whole 
milk from five grocery stores in each of the 10 cities boston 
baltimore atlanta dallas chicago kansas city denver san 
francisco seattle and new york 
of the 49 samples 36 showed some sign of the drug lecos said 
of the 36 he added only five were above trace levels 
there is no reason for the public to be concerned about the 
safety of the milk lecos said the point is we dont want to 
find it sulfamethazine in milk at all 
the effort to develop a quick and accurate test for milk 
contamination comes as the fda is conducting a larger review of 
whether sulfamethazine which has been used since the late 1950s 
to treat respiratory disease in food animals should be banned 
outright 
fda commissioner frank e young met with manufacturers of the 
drug last month to discuss the review and has convened a twoday 
hearing next month to further study the issue 
fda studies have suggested that sulfamethazine used in the feed 
of an estimated 80 percent of all hogs marketed in the united 
states can cause cancer in mice 
the agency decision to reopen the question of whether the drug 
should be allowed at all stems from those recent studies coupled 
with improved onsite agriculture department pork testing methods 
that suggest higher levels are reaching the market than earlier 
detection methods revealed 
