<TEXT>
the house gave final congressional approval 
wednesday to legislation awarding the states title to abandoned 
historic shipwrecks lying within their waters after rejecting a 
proposal to guarantee access to wrecks by sport divers and salvage 
operators 
by a 34064 vote the house passed and sent to the white house 
for president reagans signature the same measure it narrowly 
rejected two weeks ago when opponents complained they were denied 
the opportunity to offer amendments to the bill 
the bill was brought up again wednesday under different 
parliamentary ground rules that allowed consideration of 
amendments but the major proposed change the access guarantee 
sought by rep norman d shumway rcalif in behalf of sport 
divers and salvors was defeated on a 268134 roll call 
shumways adversaries had warned that approval of any amendments 
would require sending the bill back to the senate where they said 
the measure almost certainly would die shumway dismissed the 
warnings as scare tactics but the measure cleared the house 
without any changes 
before the final vote the house rejected 221183 an amendment 
by rep robert s walker rpa that would have required the 
states to give federal law enforcement agencies freedom to pursue 
drug smugglers into state coastal waters 
it also defeated by voice vote another shumway proposal to limit 
coverage to wrecks listed on or eligible for the national 
register of historic places 
the measure wouuld give states title to the estimated 5 percent 
to 10 percent of the shipwrecks in state waters that are considered 
historically important all others having no historic interest 
plus all shipwrecks lying beyond three miles offshore would be 
governed by federal admiralty law 
admiralty law awards shipwrecks and cargoes to the finders and 
permits salvage operators to claim a major portion of the cargoes 
they raise 
under the bill admiralty law would not apply to the small 
number of historically significant shipwrecks in state waters and 
indian tribes would have title to shipwrecks on their lands the 
federal government would retain title to any abandoned wrecks on 
public lands 
until now both states and federal admiralty courts have claimed 
jurisdiction over such wrecks in state waters 
the submerged lands act of 1953 gave the states ownership of all 
natural resources and submerged lands up to three miles offshore 
but did not cover manmade objects on those lands 
the house had defeated the measure march 29 by a 263139 margin 
five votes short of the twothirds majority required for passage 
under ground rules for accelerated debate with no amendments the 
rules in effect wednesday required only a simple majority for 
passage 
the bill passed the senate by voice vote on dec 19 
rep jack fields rtexas who supported the shumway amendment 
said he would urge the president to veto the bill unless it 
guaranteed the nations 4 million sport divers and latterday 
christopher columbuses the right to search state waters for 
undiscovered shipwrecks 
rep jack brooks dtexas countered that the bill already makes 
clear in a nonbinding provision that congress wants the states 
to guarantee exploration and recovery of wrecks under federal 
guidelines intended to protect historic artifacts against 
plundering by profiteers 
