the senate on wednesday kicked aside two days 
of arguments about truthinbudgeting and began expanding the war 
on drugs as it moved to finish its 11 trillion fiscal 1989 
spending plan 
leaders said they would complete action on the fiscal blueprint 
by thursday 
the senate approved 7618 on wednesday night an amendment 
cutting government travel accounts by 125 million to finance new 
federal prisons and drug law enforcement efforts 
a second 14 billion expansion of drug programs was being 
prepared for the electionyear plan 
lawmakers had been ensnarled since monday in a debate over 
whether surpluses in the social security system and other federal 
trust funds masked the extent of the deficit problem 
the budget claims a deficit of 136 billion in the fiscal year 
beginning oct 1 but it would be about 220 billion if trust fund 
earnings werent counted 
senate budget committee chairman lawton chiles dfla proposed 
that the senate go on record opposed to counting against the 
deficit the social security surpluses being built up now to be 
spent for future retirees 
other senators then loaded on amendments covering trust funds 
for aviation roadbuilding the postal service military 
retirement and the banking system 
after the accounting issue threatened to put the senate into a 
stall sen pete v domenici rnm won a substitute amendment 
it referred the issue to the new national economic commission 
which will be examining deficit issues over the next year 
the way was then cleared for other amendments including an 
expected proposal to increase spending on drug treatment and law 
enforcement by 14 billion next year 
the amendment being drafted by sens dennis deconcini dariz 
and alfonse damato rny would breach the limits of last falls 
deficit reduction agreement between president reagan and 
congressional leaders 
however the money could be allocated under a clause providing 
for dire emergencies certified by the president and congressional 
leaders the sponsors said the increased cost could be covered by 
increasing collection of debts owed the government and tax law 
enforcement 
last falls budget agreement set overall spending levels for the 
military foreign aid and domestic agencies 
in meeting those caps outside of the new drug spending the 
senate plan cut spending on some subsidies and for development and 
transportation however it also included big increases in spending 
in selected areas those include 
a 27 percent increase in the space program 11 percent more for 
national science foundation research aid and money to start work 
on the proposed superconducting super collider nuclear physics 
project 
a 19 percent boost for aviation safety including hiring more 
air traffic controllers and modernizing equipment 
an increase of 74 percent for education programs 
the pentagon under the budget agreement would spend 294 
billion and 161 billion would be spent on foreign aid 
there were no tax increases included beyond the 14 billion 
enacted last december under the agreement 
the senate and house must agree on a single budget resolution 
before it becomes final the budget which does not require the 
presidents signature becomes congress internal guideline for its 
fiscal legislation 
although this years budget resolutions are similar because of 
the deficit agreement the house and senate disagree on some 
priorities 
the house plan would provide more money for development programs 
and less for the space program the house also voted for a 3 
percent pay raise for all federal employees while the senate 
adopted reagans proposal to give the military 43 percent and 
civilian workers 2 percent 
