the nations orchestras suffer difficult financial times and turn 
to taxpayers for assistance 
the baltimore symphony has steadfastly declined to reveal 
financial details of david zinmans new sixyear contract as music 
director even though more than onethird of the orchestras 9 
million operating budget is underwritten by maryland taxpayers the 
orchestras 1986 tax return lists zinmans salary as 193500 for 
the 198586 season his first as music director 
most orchestras had similar responses to requests for comment 
the newspaper said 
weve made it a longstanding policy not to discuss any aspect 
of salaries said francis little spokesman for the new york 
philharmonic 
the newspaper quoted unidentified sources as saying that recent 
reports that lorin maazel will get 1 million per year in a 
contract set to take effect later this year at the pittsburgh 
symphony were exaggerated 
nevertheless music industry insiders believe that maazel will 
be the highest paid music director in america next fall the 
evening sun said maazels salary at pittsburgh in 1986 when he 
was only a parttime music adviser was 125000 
