<TEXT>
in the old days maple sugaring consisted 
mainly of a grove of sugar maples buckets horsedrawn sleighs to 
collect them and a wood fire to boil down the collected sap 
these days on david marvins maple farm sugaring means purple 
plastic tubing vacuum pumps and a reverse osmosis unit 
this is hightech maple sugaring maybe not as romantic as a 
bucket on a tree but much more common 
there are more and more people who are using the advanced 
technology all the time said everett willard maple marketing 
specialist for the vermont department of agriculture he estimates 
75 percent of this years sap will be sucked out through plastic 
tubing instead of dripping into a bucket 
stretching through marvins sugarbush the grove of sugar 
maples are miles of green plastic tubing attached to a vacuum 
pump two vats and an underground piping system in the sugarhouse 
a reverse osmosis unit concentrates the sap before its boiled in a 
vshaped vat with steamheated copper tubing 
last year there were counties in the state that did not have a 
reverse osmosis unit i dont know if thats true now added 
sumner williams a research technician at the university of vermont 
maple research center in underhill 
the machinery is in use right now as sugar makers ply their 
trade in the waning days of the sugaring season theyre expecting 
a good year although uncooperative weather could curb the sap 
output that will surpass last years production of 275000 
gallons although they dont expect to top the 338000 gallons 
produced in 1986 
the record production was nearly 163 million gallons in 1927 
runs in the south are looking good so far there are loads of 
sap and it has been making goodtasting syrup too 
yesterday morning i called five producers in five vermont 
towns and every one of them told me they made more than last 
year everett said recently 
up north where marvin taps sugar makers had a slow start 
producers need warm days and chilly nights for the sap to flow but 
even a daytime high of 40 degrees wasnt coaxing the clear liquid 
from the trees during a late march trip through marvins sugarbush 
the runs improved a few days later perfect sugaring weather 
sent a flood of sap from the trees and producers were boiling for 
hours on end but the good luck lasted just a few days and as 
temperatures rose it looked like production wouldnt be much better 
than the yield in 1986 
in marvins sugarbush sap tubing which is often green or 
purple stretches like a psychedelic clothesline as its strung 
from tree to tree the lines are attached to the vacuum which 
helps suck sap from the tubes the sap is stored in the two large 
vats which are piped to the sugarhouse 
the reverse osmosis machine pushes the sap through membranes so 
that the relative sugar content increases from about 2 percent to 8 
percent that means less water in the sap and a lot less boiling 
time to turn it into syrup 
such innovations have grown more common as more people take up 
sugaring a trade once dominated by dairy farmers willard 
estimates the number of tree taps has at least doubled in the last 
10 years 
vermonts maple research center runs a sugarmaking operation and 
passes on production tips through meetings and publications 
marvin whose father jim cofounded the center has tried to 
keep up with the latest technology from new machinery to better 
trees one researcher dr mariafranca morselli is doing 
laboratory tests on tree varieties 
i dont foresee my planting trees that come from a test tube 
however there is a great deal of practical application to what 
shes doing and others have been doing before shes really looking 
at the importance of genetic traits in sap production and yield and 
so forth said marvin 
marvin sees this year as a watershed in the trend toward 
hightech sugaring 
if we have a good year i see people making capital 
improvements whether its a vacuum system or an evaporator he 
said however if its a poor year i think people are going to 
be discouraged 
my hope is we have just an average year he said and 
there wont be so much maple syrup that it floods the market 
</TEXT>
