<DOCNO> AP880413-0283 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
finance leaders from the worlds top 
industrial countries met today in rare harmony for a session at 
which they were expected to reaffirm a fourmonthold pact that has 
successfully stabilized the value of the dollar 
the finance ministers and heads of the central banks of the 
seven nations were meeting at a session hosted by treasury 
secretary james a baker iii 
japanese finance minister kiichi miyazawa told reporters before 
the meeting started that he expected cordial discussions with 
little disagreement 
the conference will not be so difficult unlike the others we 
have had before he said 
german finance minister gerhard stoltenberg said he was looking 
forward to good discussions 
the meetings began with a session of the group of five 
countries the united states japan west germany britain and 
france they were joined later in the morning by italy and canada 
in the past wrangling between the countries over interest 
rates proper currency levels and trade imbalances has sent 
financial markets into an uproar 
but this time there appear to be no major disagreements 
americas allies are happy that the country is finally making 
progress to reduce its huge federal budget deficit which they 
blame for keeping world interest rates high and the reagan 
administration has been pleased that japan and west germany are 
doing more to stimulate growth in their countries actions expected 
to reduce the huge us foreign trade deficit 
the seven nations pledged dec 22 in a communique worked out 
longdistance to support the value of the dollar at its current 
leels that pact has been working lending reassurance to jittery 
financial markets 
there had been fears that the global collapse of stock markets 
on oct 19 would lead to a worldwide recession in 1988 but that 
doomsday scenario failed to materialize 
the world economy is growing at a faster pace than expected 
while a relentless downward slide in the dollar which contributed 
to last falls market turmoil has been at least temporarily halted 
the major industrial countries of the world obviously favor 
stability of exchange rates and we have been very pleased with the 
stability we have seen since december baker said monday 
while the industrial countries have repeatedly professed a 
harmony of views over the past three years their disagreements 
over currency values trade imbalances and interest rates have 
often roiled financial markets 
the administration and its economic allies launched an effort in 
september 1985 to push the value of the dollar down as a way of 
reducing the soaring us trade imbalance believing that a weaker 
dollar would curb americans appetite for imports while making us 
goods more competitive on overseas markets 
the administration formally abandoned that push in february 1987 
at a meeting in paris with its economic allies 
however the dollar continued to slide for much of 1987 often 
lurching downward with each monthly release of the latest us 
trade deficit total showing the imbalance between what the country 
imported and what it sold abroad was remaining at stubbornly high 
levels 
this convinced financial markets that despite the 
administrations public pledge it secretly wanted the dollar to go 
lower 
the falling dollar raised inflation fears in this country and 
prompted the federal reserve last september to boost interest 
rates the turmoil involving the dollar and higher interest rates 
are often cited as two factors which helped spark the october stock 
market collapse 
the collapse served as frightening evidence of the dangers in 
economic disunity and spurred a dec 22 pledge by the top economic 
powers to work harder to keep the dollar from falling further 
that commitment was backed up by massive intervention in 
currency markets the process by which governments buy weak 
currencies to prop up their value 
in addition to reaffirming the december pact the finance 
ministers are also expected to review and perhaps agree to a novel 
idea first advanced by baker last september to use the price of 
gold and other commodities to help the top economic powers 
coordinate their policies 
baker has stressed that he is not proposing a return to a gold 
standard the system by which currencies were stabilized for a 
quarter century following world war ii 
rather baker has said the commodity basket of goods should be 
added to the other economic indicators the countries have been 
using since the tokyo economic summit in 1986 to measure their 
performances this group of indicators includes individual growth 
rates inflation and trade balances 
bakers commodity basket of products including gold would 
introduce a pricesensitive measure into the economic planning 
process if commodity prices were rising in particular countries 
they would be encouraged to boost interest rates to fight 
inflation but if commodity prices were failing in certain 
countries those nations would know they had room to cut interest 
rates and stimulate economic growth 
some countries in particular west germany have opposed the 
commodity index seeing it as a device whi in one new initiative on third 
world debt world bank president 
barber conable announced tuesday the formation of a new worldwide 
agency to insure private investors against loss from war and other 
hostile actions 
conable said the new multilateral investment guarantee agency 
which will start with 108 billion would attract more direct 
investment into third world countries by issuing insurance policies 
to protect investors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

