<TEXT>
recent news coverage about several 
airlines complaints concerning defects in boeings widebody 747 
and 767 jetliners was due partly to boeings open way of dealing 
with its problems company officials say 
furthermore more boeing workers are now aware of items that 
need improving phil condit boeing commercial airplanes executive 
vice president said tuesday 
air transportation is the safest transportation mode there 
is and is getting even safer because airlines manufacturers and 
regulatory agencies work together to identify and correct problems 
condit said 
boeings news conference came one day after the federal aviation 
administration confirmed it has issued 50 airworthiness directives 
in the last two years telling airlines to fix various problems with 
boeing jets 
the most recent warning issued friday concerned possible fuel 
leaks in the cargo area of boeing 747200s the leaks can be caused 
by a bolt giving way in a wing section and airlines using the jets 
were ordered to inspect them before returning the planes to service 
boeing officials said the order applied to 317 operating 
747200s 
airlines boeing and faa officials have said none of the defects 
cited to date has been linked to a crash or other major damage 
condit said that as soon as a problem is discovered boeing 
corrects it and notifies all operators of the plane along with 
regulatory agencies 
boeing which had more than 50 percent of the worldwide 
commercial jet market last year writes about 1000 service 
bulletins annually to point out improvements or possible problems 
condit said most are minor but he said some are serious enough to 
require an airworthiness directive to ensure all carriers check for 
the problem 
condit said the recent reports presented only a snapshot 
view of boeings ongoing process of checking its planes to see how 
they can be improved 
because boeing has become more open with its work force sharing 
customer complaints and asking for employees advice on solving 
problems its more likely that word of such problems will reach 
the public he said 
in addition boeing this year started an audit of its 
aircraft testing procedures to make sure problems arent falling 
through the cracks condit said 
last year boeing added more than 3000 workers at its everett 
widebody plant bringing employment there to about 14000 said 
william shineman vice president and general manager of the everett 
division another 500 to 1000 will be hired this year he said 
he and condit acknowledged that as boeing increases 747 and 767 
production theres an increased potential for defects until 
production methods new staff and suppliers are brought to speed 
the faa monitors manufacture of us civilian aircraft to ensure 
they meet design specifications nick wantiez of the seattle faa 
office said tuesday that in recent months the agency expanded 
those investigations at boeing to include the recent airline 
complaints which range from wrong parts to incorrectly installed 
firefighting systems 
he said the most recent directive came after reports of 
complaints by japan air lines northwest airlines lufthansa air 
india aerolineas argentinas and a leasing company starting nov 
21 with a jal report in los angeles of a fuel leak involving a bolt 
that had broken from corrosion 
complaints about other problems have also been sent to boeing by 
american airlines british airways jal and all nippon a domestic 
japanese carrier 
the problems cited by all nippon included a wing flap 
disintegrating in flight on the first day of service smoke from a 
misassembled power unit that caused an emergency landing and 
problems in a fire extinguisher system 
jal and american also complained about the firesuppression 
system 
condit said all of the problems reported had been fixed 
