<TEXT>
retail sales spurred by gains at department 
stores and auto showrooms rose a strong 08 percent in march the 
fifth consecutive increase the government said today 
the commerce department said retail sales rose a seasonally 
adjusted 11 billion to 1307 billion 
sales were strong in all categories except furniture stores and 
restaurants and were well above expectations most economists 
before today predicted an increase of 02 percent to 03 percent 
the march increase came atop a 06 percent gain in february 
revised upward from the 04 percent estimate released a month ago 
the latest rise was the strongest since a 11 percent increase 
in december ever since the october stock market crash economists 
have watched retail sales closely for signs that the consumer 
sector of the economy would weaken 
but more recently some analysts have raised fears that too much 
consumer demand could refire inflation and lead to higher interest 
rates 
much of the strength in march came from sales at department and 
other general merchandise stores boosted by an earlierthanusual 
easter their sales rose 16 percent following a 26 percent 
decrease in february 
auto sales rose 09 percent following a 20 percent increase a 
month earlier excluding autos sales were up 08 percent the same 
as the overall rise 
sales of all durable goods items expected to last three or more 
years were up 05 percent while nondurable goods were up 10 
percent 
the department offered these details of march sales 
hardware and garden supply stores up 05 percent after 
soaring 30 percent in february 
furniture and appliance stores down 20 percent after a 
strong 29 percent increase a month earlier 
food and grocery stores up 11 percent after an earlier 06 
percent rise 
gasoline up 14 percent following a 12 percent decline 
specialty clothing stores up 03 percent restaurants and 
bars down 06 percent and drug stores up 16 percent 
