<TEXT>
two western pennsylvania congressmen wednesday 
introduced legislation in washington aimed at preventing investment 
firms and foreign bank holding companies from pursuing certain 
corporate takeovers 
rep doug walgren a democrat and rep tom ridge a republican 
said their proposal stemmed from the 17 billion takeover battle 
for koppers co a pittsburghbased cement and building materials 
concern 
british industrialist brian c beazer joined with shearson 
lehman hutton inc and national westminster bank plc in launching a 
bid for the company 
the congressmen said their bill would prohibit a financial 
services company that owns an federally insured bank from taking 
more than a 5 percent equity interest in a company not involved in 
financial services 
shearson owns boston safe deposit and trust co which ranks as 
the nations 20th largest bank it also owns nearly 50 percent in 
bns the company beazer formed to make the bid for koppers 
the ridgewalgren bill also would prohibit a foreign bank 
holding company that owns a federally insured bank from using its 
financial resources to acquire interest in a company not engaged in 
financial services 
if investment banks are permitted to become full partners in 
takeover efforts through an equity interest that is to go beyond 
the traditional role of lending money corporate america will be 
controlled by banks at unprecedented levels walgren said 
the bill is expected to be referred to the house banking 
committee walgrens office said ridge serves on that committee 
sen john heinz rpa has introduced similar legislation in 
the senate 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

