public service company of new hampshire 
wont flatly predict when or if its seabrook nuclear power plant 
ever will operate but the estimate it makes for financial planning 
purposes has slipped again to jan 1 1990 
that is 18 months later than public services prior written 
planning assumption though company officials told state regulators 
last year that the date had slipped at least to april 1989 
in its annual report for 1987 filed this week with the 
securities and exchange commission public service also raises the 
possibility that federal regulators would set rates if the company 
emerges successfully from bankruptcy protection and reiterates 
that rates likely would have to increase 
barred by state law from charging ratepayers for any of its 36 
percent share of the 53 billion reactor before the plant operates 
commercially and unable to borrow any more money public service 
on jan 28 became the first big investorowned utility in more than 
50 years to seek bankruptcy protection 
company spokesman nicholas ashooh emphasized on wednesday that 
the new seabrook startup assumption is not a prediction of when the 
beleaguered reactor will produce electricity 
after earlier projected startup dates repeatedly passed with 
seabrook remaining idle public service originally hoped to have 
it operating commercially in 1979 the utility in recent years has 
said it cannot predict when or if the 1150megawatt plant will 
ever surmount evacuationplanning obstacles to a license 
but in compiling its reports for the sec we just have to have 
an estimate to make some financial planning assumptions ashooh 
said 
the companys most recent previous seabrook startup assumption 
had been july 1 though utility officials had told state regulators 
during hearings on an emergency rate request last year that date 
probably would be missed 
public service was denied the seabrookrelated rate increase 
when the state supreme court upheld the law that bars utilities 
from charging ratepayers for power plants before they produce 
electricity two days later the utility new hampshires largest 
power company sought bankruptcy refuge 
public service this month appealed the state court ruling to the 
us supreme court hoping to increase the value of the company in 
reorganzation by being allowed to charge ratepayers for seabrook 
before it operates 
it is believed that some level of rate increases will be 
essential to develop and implement a successful plan the company 
told the sec 
