<TEXT>
the federal government admitted wednesday that 
it might wind up paying somebody to take the great plains coal 
gassification plant in north dakota off its hands 
allen wampler assistant secretary of energy for fossil energy 
told a house subcommittee the energy department would insist on a 
fair value for the plant and a commitment by the buyer to keep it 
operating or it wouldnt sell 
but wampler declined to say whether the department would insist 
on at least a theoretical retention value for the plant a 
value that congressional investigators estimated at about 1 
billion 
were not going to sell if it doesnt make sense to do it from 
the standpoint of fair value and the assurance of continued 
operation wampler told the energy and power subcommittee of the 
house energy and commerce committee 
rep philip sharp dind chairman of the subcommittee called 
the hearings to explore whether the administration was about to 
engage in a giveaway of the 2 billion plant that the 
department took over in 1985 when its sponsors defaulted on 16 
billion in government loans 
the plant near beulah planned in the nearpanic energy hunts of 
the late 1970s has been a technical success it produces more than 
140 million cubic feet of synthetic natural gas per day from 
lignite selling it under 25year contracts to four pipelines 
the contract price is tied to the price of heating oil recently 
the pipelines have been paying 396 per million btus of gas 
roughly 1000 cubic feet while the average wellhead price is about 
175 
the plant has been running an operational surplus of about 50 
million a year though not charging for depreciation 
in two years the contracts will change to a price just below the 
most expensive 10 percent of gas purchased by the pipelines 
the congressional general accounting office reported that net 
revenues from the project through the year 2009 using private 
forecaster assumptions on future natural gas prices had a 
theoretical value of 569 million in other words a buyer would 
pay that now in exchange for all the future net revenues 
if a private buyer is eligible for production tax credits 
granted by congress in 1980 as an incentive the governments sale 
price would have to be about 1 billion to realize a net gain of 
569 million this makes 1 billion the retention value the 
point where the government is equally well off selling the plant or 
keeping it 
to avoid jeopardizing negotiations with eight potential buyers 
the department has not stated what price it expects the 
congressional investigators said they were respecting that secrecy 
and it is therefore very important to keep in mind that we did 
not estimate the present value of the projects future cash flow to 
a private investor and that our hypothetical sale prices does not 
represent our judgment on the projects market value 
wampler said the administration philosophically favored a sale 
because there is no prevailing reason for the government to 
operate a gas plant 
asked by rep mike synar dokla whether the department would 
sell if the selling price were below theoretical value wampler 
replied i cant answer that i dont know if i would or not 
pressed then on whether he would be basically paying somebody to 
take this off your hands wampler replied with the production 
tax credits yes it would be 
